ry|Maps of voyages by Christopher Columbus}}\n* [https://www.ucalgary.ca/applied_history/tutor/eurvoya/columbus.html European Voyages of Exploration: Christopher Columbus]\n* [http://www.ericdigests.org/1992-2/voyages.htm Teaching about the Voyages of Columbus]\n* [http://www.history.com/search.do?searchText=COLUMBUS+LAST+VOYAGE Columbus's Last Voyage] on the [[History (U.S. TV channel)|History Channel]]\n\n{{Exploration}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Voyages Of Christopher Columbus}}\n[[Category:Christopher Columbus| ]]\n[[Category:1490s in North America]]\n[[Category:1490s in Spain]]\n[[Category:1490s in the Caribbean]]\n[[Category:1490s in the Spanish West Indies]]\n[[Category:1500s in North America]]\n[[Category:1500s in Spain]]\n[[Category:1500s in the Caribbean]]\n[[Category:1500s in the Spanish West Indies]]\n[[Category:Colonial Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:History of the Colony of Santo Domingo]]\n[[Category:Expeditions from Spain]]\n[[Category:Exploration of North America]]\n[[Category:Exploration of South America]]\n[[Category:History of South America]]\n[[Category:History of the Caribbean]]\n[[Category:Age of Discovery]]\n[[Category:Spanish exploration in the Age of Discovery]]\n[[Category:Spanish colonial period of Cuba]]\n", "name_user": "2601:241:8d00:f980:d851:a4c:d2bf:b23f", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Voyages_of_Christopher_Columbus"}
{"title_page": "Bells Beach, Victoria", "text_new": "{{moresources|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox Australian place | type = town \n| name     = Bells Beach\n| state    = vic\n| image    = Bells Beach 2019.jpg \n| caption  = Bells Beach hosting the Rip Curl Pro 2019\n| use_lga_map = yes\n| coordinates = {{coord|38|22|S|144|17|E|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_label_position = top\n| lga      = Surf Coast Shire\n| postcode = 3228\n| pop      = 130\n| pop_year = {{CensusAU|2016}}\n| pop_footnotes = <ref name=\"abs\">{{Census 2016 AUS | id = SSC20199 | name = Bells Beach (State Suburb) | accessdate = 17 November 2017 | quick = on}}</ref>\n| est      = \n| stategov = [[Electoral district of Polwarth|Polwarth]]\n| stategov2 = [[Electoral district of South Barwon|South Barwon]]\n| fedgov   = [[Division of Corangamite|Corangamite]]\n| dist1    = 86\n| dir1     = SW\n| location1= [[Melbourne, Victoria|Melbourne]]\n| dist2    = 25\n| dir2     = S\n| location2= [[Geelong, Victoria|Geelong]]\n| dist3    = 5\n| dir3     = SW\n| location3= [[Torquay, Victoria|Torquay]]\n| near-nw  = [[Bellbrae, Victoria|Bellbrae]]\n| near-n   = [[Bellbrae, Victoria|Bellbrae]]\n| near-ne  = [[Jan Juc, Victoria|Jan Juc]]\n| near-w   = [[Anglesea, Victoria|Anglesea]]\n| near-e   = ''[[Bass Strait]]''\n| near-sw  = ''[[Bass Strait]]''\n| near-s   = ''[[Bass Strait]]''\n| near-se  = ''[[Bass Strait]]''\n}}\n[[File:bells beach surfers.JPG|thumb|Surfers at the beach]]\n'''Bells Beach''' is a coastal locality of [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], [[Australia]] in [[Surf Coast Shire]] and a renowned [[Beach|surf beach]], located 100&nbsp;km south-west of [[Melbourne]], on the [[Great Ocean Road]] near the towns of [[Torquay, Victoria|Torquay]] and [[Jan Juc]].\n\nIt is named after William Bell, a Master Mariner, who owned much of the property there since the 1840s. Many records wrongly accredit the locations name to John Calvert Bell of the family that took up a pastoral run there much later in 1905 and building the 'Addiscot' homestead. John Calvert Bell was, before that time, a resident at Calder Park, Mount Duneed, and not related to William Bell of Bells Beach.  The beach and coastal reserve are listed on the [[Victorian Heritage Register]].<ref>[http://vhd.heritage.vic.gov.au/places/result_detail/12711 \"Bells Beach Surfing Recreation Reserve (H2261)\"]. ''[[Victorian Heritage Register]].'' [[Heritage Victoria]]. Retrieved 2014-03-23.</ref>\n\nIn the 2016 Census, there were 130 people in Bells Beach, 88.7% of whom were born in Australia and 94.5% of whom spoke only English at home.<ref name=\"abs\"/>\n\n==Surfing==\nBells Beach is the home of the world's longest continuously running pro surfing competition \u2013 now known as the Rip Curl Pro Bells Beach. The event was formerly known as the Bells Easter Classic (among a variety of other titles). The competition was first held in January 1962 and then at Easter every year since although occasionally, when conditions at Bells aren't suitable, the competition has been transferred to other breaks such as [[Johanna, Victoria|Johanna]] and Woolamai.\n\nAs early as 1939, surfers from Torquay made their way to Bells but access was a considerable problem until 1960, when Torquay surfers and Olympic wrestler Joe Sweeney hired a bulldozer and cleared a road along the Bells cliff <ref>Heritage Council of Victoria Annual Report 2003-04</ref> from the Cobb & Co Road, where the concrete wave now stands, down to the beach. He charged one pound per surfer to recover his expenses. This is now part of the Surf Coast walking track.\n\nNearby surf breaks include \"Southside\", \"Centreside\", \"Rincon\", \"Winki Pop\", (Uppers and Lowers), \"Boobs\" and \"Steps\".  Although Bells is known internationally as one of the best breaks in Victoria, \"Winki Pop\" often works better under more diverse conditions than the other nearby breaks.{{Citation needed|date=December 2009}}\n\nThe first \"Surfboard Rally\" at Bells Beach was organised by surfing pioneers Peter Troy and Vic Tantau to help promote sales of T Boards their own brand. Planned to run in December 1961 the event was postponed until 26 January 1962. From the following year the Australian Surf rider's Association - ASA (Victorian Branch) - Now called Surfing Victoria hosted and staged the annual surfing competition at Bells Beach held at Easter each year. The ASA also ran the conservation contest at Bells Beach which included tree planting in an effort to help preserve natural values every year since the mid-1970s.\n\n===Surfing competitions===\n* [[Rip Curl]] GromSearch National Series (under 17s) \n* [[Rip Curl Pro]] every Easter since 1962\n\n===Surfers Appreciating the Natural Environment (SANE)===\nIn 1988 a group of local surfers who were concerned about the human impact that tourism was having on the Bells Beach Surfing Reserve started a group called Surfers Appreciating the Natural Environment. Since 1988 they have met monthly to revegetate the reserve in an effort to bring it back to its original state. They have planted over 100,000 plants there to date.\n\n==In popular culture==\nAlthough the final scene of the film ''[[Point Break (1991 film)|Point Break]]'' is set at Bells Beach, the scene was not filmed there.  Bells Beach is a straight stretch and the beach in the film is a cove with spruce trees atop a hill.  The actual location of the film was a beach called Indian Beach, in [[Lewis and Clark National and State Historical Parks#Ecola State Park|Ecola State Park]], located in [[Cannon Beach, Oregon]], [[United States]].\n\nBells Beach is visited in the 1966 documentary film ''[[The Endless Summer]]''.\n\nIn the 2007 animation film ''[[Surf's Up (film)|Surf's Up]]'', the Australian surfer is shown to be from Bells Beach.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.visitvictoria.com/Regions/Great-Ocean-Road/Activities-and-attractions/Nature-and-wildlife/Beaches-and-coastlines/Bells-Beach.aspx Bells Beach - Tourism site]\n*[http://www.janjuc.com.au Torquay,Jan Juc,Bells Beach Visitor Guide - JanJuc.com.au]\nBells Beach Facebook community - [http://www.facebook.com/bellsbeachtorquay www.facebook.com/bellsbeachtorquay]\n\n{{Towns in Surf Coast Shire}}\n{{Australiansurf}}\n{{Great Ocean Road}}\n\n[[Category:Surfing_locations]]\n[[Category:Towns in Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Coastal towns in Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Surfing locations in Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Beaches of Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Victorian Heritage Register]]\n", "text_old": "{{moresources|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox Australian place | type = town \n| name     = Bells Beach\n| state    = vic\n| image    = Bells Beach 2019.jpg \n| caption  = Bells Beach hosting the Rip Curl Pro 2019\n| use_lga_map = yes\n| coordinates = {{coord|38|22|S|144|17|E|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_label_position = top\n| lga      = Surf Coast Shire\n| postcode = 3228\n| pop      = 130\n| pop_year = {{CensusAU|2016}}\n| pop_footnotes = <ref name=\"abs\">{{Census 2016 AUS | id = SSC20199 | name = Bells Beach (State Suburb) | accessdate = 17 November 2017 | quick = on}}</ref>\n| est      = \n| stategov = [[Electoral district of Polwarth|Polwarth]]\n| stategov2 = [[Electoral district of South Barwon|South Barwon]]\n| fedgov   = [[Division of Corangamite|Corangamite]]\n| dist1    = 86\n| dir1     = SW\n| location1= [[Melbourne, Victoria|Melbourne]]\n| dist2    = 25\n| dir2     = S\n| location2= [[Geelong, Victoria|Geelong]]\n| dist3    = 5\n| dir3     = SW\n| location3= [[Torquay, Victoria|Torquay]]\n| near-nw  = [[Bellbrae, Victoria|Bellbrae]]\n| near-n   = [[Bellbrae, Victoria|Bellbrae]]\n| near-ne  = [[Jan Juc, Victoria|Jan Juc]]\n| near-w   = [[Anglesea, Victoria|Anglesea]]\n| near-e   = ''[[Bass Strait]]''\n| near-sw  = ''[[Bass Strait]]''\n| near-s   = ''[[Bass Strait]]''\n| near-se  = ''[[Bass Strait]]''\n}}\n[[File:bells beach surfers.JPG|thumb|Surfers at the beach]]\n'''Bells Beach''' is a coastal locality of [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], [[Australia]] in [[Surf Coast Shire]] and a renowned [[Beach|surf beach]], located 100&nbsp;km south-west of [[Melbourne]], on the [[Great Ocean Road]] near the towns of [[Torquay, Victoria|Torquay]] and [[Jan Juc]].\n\nIt is named after William Bell, a Master Mariner, who owned much of the property there since the 1840s. Many records wrongly accredit the locations name to John Calvert Bell of the family that took up a pastoral run there much later in 1905 and building the 'Addiscot' homestead. John Calvert Bell was, before that time, a resident at Calder Park, Mount Duneed, and not related to William Bell of Bells Beach.  The beach and coastal reserve are listed on the [[Victorian Heritage Register]].<ref>[http://vhd.heritage.vic.gov.au/places/result_detail/12711 \"Bells Beach Surfing Recreation Reserve (H2261)\"]. ''[[Victorian Heritage Register]].'' [[Heritage Victoria]]. Retrieved 2014-03-23.</ref>\n\nIn the 2016 Census, there were 130 people in Bells Beach, 88.7% of whom were born in Australia and 94.5% of whom spoke only English at home.<ref name=\"abs\"/>\n\n==Surfing==\nBells Beach is the home of the world's longest continuously running pro surfing competition \u2013 now known as the Rip Curl Pro Bells Beach. The event was formerly known as the Bells Easter Classic (among a variety of other titles). The competition was first held in January 1962 and then at Easter every year since although occasionally, when conditions at Bells aren't suitable, the competition has been transferred to other breaks such as [[Johanna, Victoria|Johanna]] and Woolamai.\n\nAs early as 1939, surfers from Torquay made their way to Bells but access was a considerable problem until 1960, when Torquay surfers and Olympic wrestler Joe Sweeney hired a bulldozer and cleared a road along the Bells cliff <ref>Heritage Council of Victoria Annual Report 2003-04</ref> from the Cobb & Co Road, where the concrete wave now stands, down to the beach. He charged one pound per surfer to recover his expenses. This is now part of the Surf Coast walking track.\n\nNearby surf breaks include \"Southside\", \"Centreside\", \"Rincon\", \"Winki Pop\", (Uppers and Lowers), \"Boobs\" and \"Steps\".  Although Bells is known internationally as one of the best breaks in Victoria, \"Winki Pop\" often works better under more diverse conditions than the other nearby breaks.{{Citation needed|date=December 2009}}\n\nThe first \"Surfboard Rally\" at Bells Beach was organised by surfing pioneers Peter Troy and Vic Tantau to help promote sales of T Boards their own brand. Planned to run in December 1961 the event was postponed until 26 January 1962. From the following year the Australian Surf rider's Association - ASA (Victorian Branch) - Now called Surfing Victoria hosted and staged the annual surfing competition at Bells Beach held at Easter each year. The ASA also ran the conservation contest at Bells Beach which included tree planting in an effort to help preserve natural values every year since the mid-1970s.\n\n===Surfing competitions===\n* [[Rip Curl]] GromSearch National Series (under 17s) \n* [[Rip Curl Pro]] every Easter since 1962\n\n===Surfers Appreciating the Natural Environment (SANE)===\nIn 1988 a group of local surfers who were concerned about the human impact that tourism was having on the Bells Beach Surfing Reserve started a group called Surfers Appreciating the Natural Environment. Since 1988 they have met monthly to revegetate the reserve in an effort to bring it back to its original state. They have planted over 100,000 plants there to date.\n\n==In popular culture==\nAlthough the final scene of the film ''[[Point Break (1991 film)|Point Break]]'' is set at Bells Beach, the scene was not filmed there.  Bells Beach is a straight stretch and the beach in the film is a cove with spruce trees atop a hill.  The actual location of the film was a beach called Indian Beach, in [[Lewis and Clark National and State Historical Parks#Ecola State Park|Ecola State Park]], located in [[Cannon Beach, Oregon]], [[United States]].\n\nBells Beach is visited in the 1966 documentary film ''[[The Endless Summer]]''.\n\nIn the 2007 animation film ''[[Surf's Up (film)|Surf's Up]]'', the Australian surfer is shown to be from Bells Beach.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.visitvictoria.com/Regions/Great-Ocean-Road/Activities-and-attractions/Nature-and-wildlife/Beaches-and-coastlines/Bells-Beach.aspx Bells Beach - Tourism site]\n*[http://www.janjuc.com.au Torquay,Jan Juc,Bells Beach Visitor Guide - JanJuc.com.au]\nBells Beach Facebook community - [http://www.facebook.com/bellsbeachtorquay www.facebook.com/bellsbeachtorquay]\n\n{{Towns in Surf Coast Shire}}\n{{Australiansurf}}\n{{Great Ocean Road}}\n\n[[Category:Towns in Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Coastal towns in Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Surfing locations in Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Beaches of Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Victorian Heritage Register]]\n", "name_user": "Richaldito", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bells_Beach,_Victoria"}
{"title_page": "Glisha Kostovski", "text_new": "<br />{{Infobox person\n| name               = Glisha Kostovski\n| image              = Glisha02.jpg\n| native_name_lang   = \u0413\u043b\u0438\u0448\u0430 \u041a\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\n| birth_place        = [[Tetovo]], [[Yugoslavia]]\n| nationality        = [[Macedonian]]\n| education          = Academy for wood crafters in Belgrade\n| awards             = Belgrade exhibition of crafters of Yugoslavia\n}}\n\n'''Glisha Kostovski,''' during the [[Serbia in the Balkan Wars|Serbian]] times '''Glisha Kostich''' was [[Macedonians (ethnic group)|Macedonian]] wood carper, with his guard he has made some of the most impressive wood carvings in [[Yugoslavia]]. He was born in the city of [[Tetovo]]. His wood carvings were mostly done for private purposes but with the economical development of the country, he started making carvings for Government and Churches. In the beginning, his work was not very respected, but close to his death, he started earning a lot, although his guard had continued to operate they were not successful.\n\n== His works ==\n[[File:Glisha04.jpg|thumb|Honour to Glisha Kostovski from Belgarde association of Yugoslavian crafters]]\nHis works can be found in a lot of churches in [[North Macedonia|Macedonia]], but the most important works can be found in two main cathedrals of the [[Macedonian Orthodox Church \u2013 Ohrid Archbishopric|Orthodox church of Macedonia]], [[Saint Jovan Bigorski Monastery]] and Church of the Holy Mother of God. His most impressive work can be found in the building of the [[Politics of North Macedonia|Government of the Republic of North Macedonia]].\n\nHis works were mostly made from [[chestnut]] trees, but also from apple trees which are characteristic for the western parts of [[North Macedonia|Macedonia]].\n\n=== The Dealborez Hall in the Governmental building. ===\n[[File:Glisha03.jpg|left|thumb|290x290px|His work presenting Cleopatra]]\n[[File:Glisha05.jpg|left|thumb|253x253px|His work]]\nThe Hall is known as the most impressive works in Macedonia. The hall is known as a favorite of many presidents of the Government. The most known situation is with the ex. US president [[Bill Clinton]]. During the 2001 [[2001 insurgency in Macedonia|Conflict in Macedonia]], the US president visited the Macedonian Government. When he had entered the room he had been fascinated by the beauty and he asked for a chair. He had been seating for a while and he had said that this is one of the most wonderful things he had seen in his life.<ref>{{Citation|title=\u041f\u0430\u043b\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u0421\u043e\u0431\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435\u0442\u043e \u043d\u0430 \u041c\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043d\u0438\u0458\u0430|date=2019-02-25|url=https://mk.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=%D0%9F%D0%B0%D0%BB%D0%B0%D1%82%D0%B0_%D0%BD%D0%B0_%D0%A1%D0%BE%D0%B1%D1%80%D0%B0%D0%BD%D0%B8%D0%B5%D1%82%D0%BE_%D0%BD%D0%B0_%D0%9C%D0%B0%D0%BA%D0%B5%D0%B4%D0%BE%D0%BD%D0%B8%D1%98%D0%B0&oldid=3823635|work=\u0412\u0438\u043a\u0438\u043f\u0435\u0434\u0438\u0458\u0430|language=mk|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\nThe Delaborez Hall is part of the Cabinet of the President of the Assembly and is used for the protocol needs of the Speaker of the Assembly of the Republic of Macedonia.\n\n=== Interior ===\nThe decoration of the hall was designed and designed from 1935 to 1937. Performed in 1938 by Glisha Kostovski, a carpenter and carpenter from [[Tetovo]], who did all his work with his typhoon. The walls and ceiling are fully lined with shallow wood and deep carving, with ornamental content incorporated and applied geometric, vegetable and other motifs.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2014-12|title=\u0414\u0430\u043d\u0438\u043b\u043e\u0432 \u0421.\u042e. \u041a\u0430\u0431\u0438\u043d\u0435\u0442 \u043f\u0430\u0440\u043b\u0430\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043c\u0435\u043d\u044c\u0448\u0438\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430: \u0441\